{"type":"text","timestamp":1773351720215,"sessionID":"ses_31c00ea90ffeMcRFqNZY7ExB1k","part":{"id":"prt_ce3ffa347002t5U6571CX8iZFd","sessionID":"ses_31c00ea90ffeMcRFqNZY7ExB1k","messageID":"msg_ce3ff9b91001YQPcOjUShbDcDp","type":"text","text":"Looking at the code again, I see that the `--version` flag handling IS already there (lines 428-438). But there's a subtle problem: the `parseArgs` function treats `--version` as a flag at line 233-235 that **consumes the next argument**:\n\n```typescript\ncase \"--version\":\n    result.version = args[++i];\n    break;\n```\n\nThis means if someone runs `wombo upgrade --version v1.0.0`, the `--version` flag correctly sets the version for the upgrade command. But if someone runs `wombo --version`, it works because `--version` becomes `args.command`, and the switch case in the parseArgs loop doesn't fire (it's at position 0, loop starts at 1).\n\nHowever, there's a problem: `-V` is NOT handled in `parseArgs` as a flag alias. If someone tries `wombo launch -V`, it would be ignored. But the main use case (`wombo -V` and `wombo --version`) already works. The feature spec says to \"add --version/-V flag\" which implies it doesn't exist yet, but it clearly does. The spec might have been written before the code was added.\n\nLet me check if there's an issue with `-V` specifically in parseArgs. Actually, `-V` is not handled in the switch inside parseArgs at all. If someone does `wombo -V`, it becomes `args.command = \"-V\"`, and the main function handles it. Good. But what if someone already has a command and adds `-V`? That's an edge case not worth worrying about since standard CLIs treat `--version` as a top-level flag only.\n\nLooking at the current implementation more carefully, I think the implementation is already present but might need refinement. The feature spec says to add it, so let me check if there's something subtle I'm missing. Let me re-read the feature description: \"wombo --version shows 'Unknown command' + full help dump. Should print the version from package.json and exit.\"\n\nThis suggests the original code didn't have the handler. Since it's there now, perhaps it was added in a recent commit. Let me check:","time":{"start":1773351720215,"end":1773351720215}}}
