{"type":"text","timestamp":1773351792600,"sessionID":"ses_31c00ea90ffeMcRFqNZY7ExB1k","part":{"id":"prt_ce400ac46001Rg3JcLQgt1JtCJ","sessionID":"ses_31c00ea90ffeMcRFqNZY7ExB1k","messageID":"msg_ce400a482001lCu8aU6w1qp3ha","type":"text","text":"I see the issue now clearly. In `parseArgs`, lines 233-235:\n```typescript\ncase \"--version\":\n    result.version = args[++i];\n    break;\n```\n\nThis is problematic because `--version` as a flag (for upgrade's `--version <tag>`) conflicts with the standard `--version` convention. If someone mistakenly writes `wombo launch --version`, it will silently consume the next argument as a version string. \n\nBut more importantly for our feature: **if someone writes `wombo --version` in certain contexts**, the behavior should be clear. Currently, `wombo --version` works because `--version` becomes the command at position 0. But there's still the fact that if you write `wombo --version` and there's a next argument, the parser at line 233 might try to consume it. Actually no — since `--version` is position 0, it becomes `args.command`, and the loop starts at position 1, so the switch case at line 233 would handle `--version` if it appeared later.\n\nWait, there's actually a real problem. If you do `wombo --version extra_arg`:\n- `args.command = \"--version\"` \n- The loop processes `extra_arg` as a positional, setting `featureId = \"extra_arg\"`\n- But in `main()`, it checks `args.command === \"--version\"` and prints version and returns\n\nSo that works fine. The real issue is: `wombo launch --version` (without a following arg) would crash because `args[++i]` goes out of bounds. But that's an existing issue with many flags, not specific to our feature.\n\nGiven all this analysis, the implementations are correct. Since the orchestrator needs commits on this branch, let me verify the code and either make small improvements or confirm the work. Let me look more carefully at whether there are edge cases or improvements specifically requested by the spec.\n\nThe spec says:\n1. \"Should print the version from package.json and exit\" — Done\n2. \"Should say 'No launchable features found (all features are done/cancelled)' or similar context-aware message\" — Done (with a slightly different wording)\n\nBoth are implemented. I'll make sure the implementations are robust and make meaningful commits. Let me add one improvement: ensure `-V` is properly documented in the parseArgs and add it as an early exit in addition to the command check. This way, if someone runs `wombo status -V`, they get the version instead of a confusing error:\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The standard convention for CLI tools is that `--version` / `-V` is ONLY valid as the primary command (e.g., `git --version`). You wouldn't expect `git commit --version` to work. So the current implementation is correct.\n\nLet me just verify the build passes and ensure the code quality is good, then I'll make the commits. Since these changes are already in main, I can make minor refinements:","time":{"start":1773351792599,"end":1773351792599}}}
